{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"9e2b7c15c9518bb2","type":"text","text":"Transaction Inner detales\n### **1. The Write-Ahead Log (WAL)**\n\nBefore Postgres changes any data in a table, it writes the intent to a log file called the **WAL**.\n\n- **The Process:** `Change Request` → `Write to WAL (Disk)` → `Update Data in Memory (Buffer)` → `Success Response`.\n    \n- **Why?** Writing to a sequential log file is much faster than searching for a specific row in a giant table. If the server crashes, Postgres replays the WAL to restore the database to its last consistent state.\n    \n\n### **2. Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC)**\n\nThis is how Postgres allows multiple people to read and write at the same time without locking the whole database.\n\n- **The \"Hidden\" Columns:** Every row in Postgres has hidden system columns, most notably `xmin` and `xmax`.\n    \n    - **`xmin`:** The ID of the transaction that **created** the row.\n        \n    - **`xmax`:** The ID of the transaction that **deleted/updated** the row.\n        \n- **The Logic:** When you run a query, Postgres looks at your transaction ID and only shows you rows where:\n    \n    1. The `xmin` is committed and less than your ID.\n        \n    2. The `xmax` is empty or belongs to a transaction that hasn't committed yet.\n        \n\n---\n\n### **3. The Transaction Life Cycle**\n\n1. **BEGIN:** Postgres assigns a unique **Transaction ID (XID)**.\n    \n2. **EXECUTION:** * For an **UPDATE**, Postgres doesn't actually overwrite the old row. It marks the old row as \"expired\" (sets `xmax`) and inserts a brand-new row (sets `xmin`) with the updated data.\n    \n3. **COMMIT:**\n    \n    - Postgres writes a \"Commit\" record to the **WAL**.\n        \n    - The data is now \"visible\" to other transactions.\n        \n4. **CLEANUP (Vacuum):**\n    \n    - Because \"updated\" rows are actually just new rows, the old \"expired\" rows stay on the disk as \"bloat.\"\n        \n    - The **Background Vacuum** process eventually comes by to delete these dead rows and reclaim space.\n        \n\n---\n\n### **Summary\n\n- **Postgres doesn't overwrite data; it versions it.** (This is why it's called Multi-Version).\n    \n- **Readers never block Writers, and Writers never block Readers.**\n    \n- **WAL is for Safety:** Ensuring we don't lose data on a crash.\n    \n- **Vacuum is for Maintenance:** Cleaning up the \"ghost\" rows left behind by updates/deletes.","x":-160,"y":-100,"width":522,"height":1540},
		{"id":"9b5ae89fd9f25879","type":"text","text":"## # ROW-LEVEL LOCK\n\nIn PostgreSQL, **Row-Level Locking** is the mechanism that prevents two people from updating the same piece of data at the exact same microsecond.\n\n### How it works:\n\n1. **The \"First Come, First Served\" Rule:** When a transaction starts an `UPDATE` or `DELETE` on a specific row, it \"grabs\" a lock on that row.\n    \n2. **The Queue:** If 9 other people try to update that same row, they don't crash. They simply **pause** and wait for the first person to either `COMMIT` (save) or `ROLLBACK` (cancel).\n    \n3. **The Hand-off:** Once the first person is done, the lock is released, and the next person in line \"wakes up,\" grabs the lock, and performs their update.\n    \n\n---\n\n### Key Interview Points:\n\n- **Reads are Free:** Because of MVCC, people can still **read** the row while it is locked for writing. They just see the \"old\" version of the data. **Readers never block writers, and writers never block readers.**\n    \n- **Minimal Impact:** Postgres is smart—it only locks the specific rows being changed, not the entire table. This allows thousands of people to use the same table simultaneously as long as they are hitting different rows.\n    \n- **Deadlocks:** If Person A locks Row 1 and wants Row 2, while Person B locks Row 2 and wants Row 1, they will wait forever. Postgres detects this \"Deadlock\" within seconds and automatically kills one of the transactions to break the loop.\n    \n\n---\n\n### The \"One-Sentence\" Summary:\n\n> \"Row-level locking ensures data integrity by forcing concurrent writers to wait in a queue for the same resource, while MVCC ensures that readers stay fast by letting them see older versions of that data without waiting.\"","x":380,"y":-100,"width":560,"height":1220},
		{"id":"a327a9608cf7ecb3","type":"text","text":"### **A - Atomicity (\"All or Nothing\")**\n\n- **Definition:** A transaction is treated as a single unit. It either completes entirely or fails entirely.\n    \n- **How Postgres does it:** It uses **WAL (Write-Ahead Logging)**. Before any changes are made to the actual data files, they are recorded in the log. If a crash occurs or a `ROLLBACK` is issued, Postgres uses these logs to undo uncommitted changes.\n    \n\n### **C - Consistency (\"Rules are Followed\")**\n\n- **Definition:** A transaction must move the database from one valid state to another, maintaining all predefined rules (constraints, cascades, triggers).\n    \n- **How Postgres does it:** It enforces **Constraints** (Unique, Foreign Key, Check, Not Null) at the moment of commitment. If a transaction violates a \"Primary Key\" rule, Postgres aborts the entire operation to prevent data corruption.\n    \n\n### **I - Isolation (\"Don't Touch My Stuff\")**\n\n- **Definition:** Concurrent transactions should not interfere with each other.\n    \n- **How Postgres does it:** This is where **MVCC** shines. Instead of locking rows (which slows things down), Postgres creates a \"snapshot\" of the data for each transaction.\n    \n    - If Transaction A is updating a row, Transaction B can still read the _old_ version of that row without waiting.\n        \n    - Postgres supports isolation levels: `Read Committed` (default), `Repeatable Read`, and `Serializable`.\n        \n\n### **D - Durability (\"Saved Forever\")**\n\n- **Definition:** Once a transaction is committed, it remains committed even in the event of a power loss or system crash.\n    \n- **How Postgres does it:** When you `COMMIT`, Postgres ensures the data is \"flushed\" to the **WAL** on physical disk storage. Even if the database server loses power a millisecond later, the record exists in the logs and will be recovered upon restart.","x":-1880,"y":-100,"width":540,"height":1120},
		{"id":"dabbfd83fa068a13","type":"text","text":"### The ACID x PostgreSQL Mapping\n\n| **Letter**      | **What it means**           | **The \"Background\" Hero**                                                                                                                                                                                        |\n| --------------- | --------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **A**tomicity   | \"All or nothing.\"           | **The Commit Log (CLOG)**: Postgres keeps a record of every transaction ID and whether it succeeded or failed. If a crash happens mid-way, Postgres checks the CLOG and ignores anything not marked \"Committed.\" |\n| **C**onsistency | Data must follow rules.     | **Constraints & Triggers**: This is handled by the database engine enforcing your Foreign Keys, Unique constraints, and Check constraints before allowing a `COMMIT`.                                            |\n| **I**solation   | Transactions don't \"leak.\"  | **MVCC & Snapshots**: As we discussed, the **xmin/xmax** and **Row-Level Locking** ensure that your transaction feels like it’s the only one running.                                                            |\n| **D**urability  | Once saved, it's permanent. | **WAL (Write-Ahead Log)**: Even if the server loses power, the sequential log on the disk ensures the data can be \"replayed\" into the database upon restart.                                                     |","x":-1280,"y":-100,"width":760,"height":620},
